foia:ProcessedRequestSection.foia:FootnoteText: As noted above in the Executive Summary, during this fiscal year DOL initiated a review of the data in its FOIA tracking system and identified 996 FOIA requests that were pending in the system and required action. Those requests are now accounted for in this report. Specifically, in FY2011 DOL reported 1,143 FOIA requests pending at the end of the fiscal year. This year DOL is reporting 2,139 requests pending at the start of FY2012. The difference between these numbers represents the 996 requests discovered as a part of the data audit.

foia:OldestPendingRequestSection.foia:FootnoteText: As part of the audit of data in Departmental FOIA tracking system, DOL located 996 requests that remined pending in the system and requiring further action, many of which were received in prior years. Whereas DOL's FY2011 report identified the 10 oldest pending requests it believed to be pending at the end of FY2011, after the addition of 548 FOIA requests identified as part of the audit, DOL is now reporting 21 additional requests that should have been previously reported.

Some work day ranges reported appear to be out of sequence based on the date of the receipt of the request. However, this is attributed to request that have been "tolled" for clarification or to resolve fee matters consistent with the provisions of the statute.

foia:BacklogSection.foia:FootnoteText: DOL was able to achieve a substantial drop in backlogged initial requests, despite having added to the data 996 pending requests that had not, but should have, been included in the FY2011 Annual FOIA report as discussed in the Executive Summary. Whereas all of DOL had 1,430 backlogged requests at the end of FY2011 (as indicated by the updated data), by the end of FY2012, the backlog had been halved down to 735 pending requests. This is attributed to more robust oversight of the departmental oversight of FOIA, the hard work of DOL’s FOIA staff, consistent monitoring of FOIA related performance measures, and sustained effort toward backlog reduction throughout the Department’s 23 FOIA components.

DOL experienced a substantial increase from only 87 backlogged appeals pending at the end of FY2011, up to 139 backlogged pending as of the end of FY2012. This is attributed to a substantial increase among the number of incoming FOIA appeals received. Further, due to the nature and complexity of the incoming FOIA appeals the number of FOIA appeals processed decreased from 393 in FY2011 to 354 in FY2012. DOL is looking for ways to address issues regarding the processing of incoming FOIA appeals.

foia:ProcessedConsultationSection.foia:FootnoteText: As a part of the audit of data in Departmental FOIA tracking system, DOL located 996 requests that remained pending in the system and requiring further action, many of which were received in prior years. Whereas DOL's FY2011 report identified 6 consultations at the end of FY2011, after the addition of 548 FOIA requests identified as part of the audit, DOL is now reporting 12 additional consultations that should have been previously reported.

foia:ProcessedRequestComparisonSection.foia:FootnoteText: As a part of the audit of data in Departmental FOIA tracking system, DOL located 996 requests that remained pending in the system and requiring further action, many of which were received in prior years. Whereas DOL’s FY2011 report stated that 18,012 FOIA requests were received during FY2011, after the addition of 548 FOIA requests identified as part of the audit, DOL is now reporting that 18,560 requests were received in FY2011.

As part of the audit of data in the Departmental FOIA tracking system, DOL identified 371 requests that had been fully processed in FY2011 but not fully closed out in the system. Whereas DOL’s FY2011 report stated that 18,129 FOIA requests were processed during FY2011, after the addition of 371 requests identified as part of the audit, DOL is now reporting that a total of 18,500 requests were fully processed during FY2011.

foia:BackloggedRequestComparisonSection.foia:FootnoteText: As a part of the audit of data in Departmental FOIA tracking system, DOL located 996 requests that remained pending in the system and requiring further action many of which were received in prior years. Whereas DOL’s FY2011 report stated that 593 backlogged request were pending at the end of FY2011, after the addition of 837 backlogged requests identified as part of the audit, DOL is now reporting that a total of 1,430 backlogged request were pending at the end of FY2011.

foia:BackloggedAppealComparisonSection.foia:FootnoteText: As a part of the overall improvement of DOL’s decentralized FOIA program, OIS continues to promote initiatives that are aimed at improving the FOIA administrative processes across DOL. The Department continues to work towards: improved customer service to our internal and external customers by providing clear and consistent FOIA responses; increased transparency by continuing to make discretionary disclosures of information where there is no foreseeable harm; and expanding DOL affirmative disclosures through the agency website and other mechanisms. DOL has also established robust process measures to closely monitor the timeliness of FOIA processing and backlog reduction.

As discussed in the Executive Summary, during FY2012 OIS initiated an audit of the Department’s FOIA data and located a large number of records that had not been properly logged into the FOIA tracking system. While this audit did change some numbers previously reported, we believe that this review resulted in the most accurate data for the purposes of FOIA reporting, ensured that all FOIA requests received by the Department are answered as accurately and completely as possible and gave an opportunity for OIS to address data reconciliation issues and make it a part of our regularly scheduled program reviews. In light of all this, the Department still managed to process more requests than it received and close all of the 10 oldest FOIA requests reported in the FY2011 report. Also, in light of the data audit, DOL was able to make a substantial reduction in the overall backlog, closing a total of 695 backlogged requests.
